<div class="col-12">
    <h1 class="text-center">Stephen Covey's Time Management Matrix</h1>
</div>

<div class="container mt-5">

    <!-- Quadrant I -->
    <div class="row mt-3">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h3>Quadrant I: Important / Urgent</h3>
            <p>Tasks that fall into this category include crises, pressing problems, and projects with deadlines. These are the tasks that require immediate attention and carry significant consequences if not addressed promptly.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Quadrant II -->
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h3>Quadrant II: Important / Not Urgent</h3>
            <p>Quadrant II tasks are important for long-term success and include relationship building, planning, and recreation. These are important but do not require immediate action and should be scheduled to do proactively.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Quadrant III -->
    <div class="row mt-3">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h3>Quadrant III: Not Important / Urgent</h3>
            <p>This quadrant includes interruptions, some phone calls, some mail, and some reports. These are tasks that demand attention but are not necessarily important to your personal goals or objectives.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Quadrant IV -->
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h3>Quadrant IV: Not Important / Not Urgent</h3>
            <p>Quadrant IV consists of activities like busy work, some mail, and time wasters. These are the least productive tasks and should be minimized or eliminated.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<br />
<br />

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-6">
        <p>
            Stephen Covey's "The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People" is a definitive guide to personal development and leadership. The book, since its first publication, has transformed the lives of presidents, CEOs, educators, and individuals all over the world with its profound, yet clear principles. Covey's approach does not focus on changing the outward behavior of individuals but instead delves into the character and habits that form the very core of each person. The habits range from private victories like being proactive, beginning with the end in mind, and putting first things first, to public victories of thinking win-win, seeking to understand then to be understood, and synergizing with others.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-6">
        <p>
            The book not only provides insights into personal effectiveness but also offers wisdom on how to manage time, make decisions, and balance work and life. Covey introduces the concept of the Time Management Matrix, urging readers to evaluate their tasks based on urgency and importance. This matrix has become a cornerstone in time management practices, helping individuals prioritize their work and focus on what truly matters. The principles outlined in the book are timeless and continue to be relevant in today's fast-paced, ever-changing world.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>
